name: optical-remote-sensing-laboratory
notes: The Optical Remote Sensing Laboratory deploys rugged, cutting-edge electro-optical instrumentation for the collection of various event signatures, with expertise in battlespace combustion and other transient events. Research areas include developing hyperspectral imagers, classification of high explosives from detonation spectra and imagery, passive ranging, laser propagation, engine, rocket and smokestack plume signatures, and chemical agent detection. A full suite of imagers, spectrometers, and radiometers spanning the visible to long wave infrared are available including: (1) A Telops FIRST-MWE imaging FTIR instrument with InSb focal plan array to capture spectra in the 1850 6667 cm-1 band at each pixel on a 320 x 256 InSb imager capable of 0.25 cm-1 spectral resolution and full hyperspectral data cubes at rates up to 20 Hz, (2) Fast Scanning Fourier Transform Infrared Spectrometers (Visible, Near, Mid and Far IR) coupled to 4.9, 28, or 75 mrad FOV telescopes, (3) a visible spectrometer system coupled to a 2 rdquo;-diameter Cassegrain telescope, (4) an Xenics XEVA InGaAs FPA at 350 Hz , (5) high speed (160kHz) visible cameras, (6) a Santa Barbara InSb FPA at 10.4 kHz, and (7) a multichannel high speed radiometers with Si, InAs, InSb, and MCT detectors.
title: Optical Remote Sensing Laboratory
